## Main

Using statistics

Descriptive statistics focuses on summarising and organising sample data to describe it's main features. Like graphs charts and other summaries.

Measures of central tendency, e.g. mean, median, mode

Measure of dispersion, range, variance, standard deviation

Measures of position, percentiles, quartiles

Inferential statistics, make predictions or inferences about a population based on a sample of data.

Estimation

Point estimations

Interval estimation, provide a range within which the parameter is expected to lie

Hypothesis testing

Forming a null(H0) and alternative(H1) hypotheses

Determine the likelihood that the sample data supports the null hypothesis

Significance tests

T-tests - compare between two groups

ANOVA(Analytics of variance) Compare means for three or more groups

Chi-squared tests.  Asses relationships between categorical variables

Regression analysis: Model the relationship between dependent and independent variables to predict outcomes

Population all the entities of investigation

Sample subset of population

- μ (mu): Represents the population mean. It’s the average value of a variable in the entire population.
- σ (sigma): Denotes the population standard deviation. It measures the spread or variability of data points in the population.
- x̄ (x bar): Refers to the sample mean. It’s the average value of a variable in a sample.
- s: Represents the sample standard deviation. Like σ but calculated from a sample.
- n: Stands for the sample size. It indicates how many observations are in a sample.
- p-value: An important concept in hypothesis testing.
- Z-score (z): Measures how many standard deviations a data point is from the mean.

Median middle value or average of two middle values. Not sensitive to outlier but doesn't use all data

Mode useful for categorical data but not useful where all values are unique, less information for multimodal distributions.

![Examples of skewness: positive skew, symmetrical distribution, and negative skew. Positive skew is skewed to the left with mode at the highest point, then median, and finally mean. Symmetrical distribution has the mode, median, and mean are clustered around the peak. Negative skew is skewed to the right with the mean the lower value that the median and mode.](data:image/png;base64,)

To calculate the skewness

![The formula for calculating the skewness of a dataset. It shows a fraction where the numerator is n (the number of observations) and the denominator is the product (n-1)(n-2). This is multiplied by the sum Σ((x - x̄)³ / s), where x are the individual data points, x-bar is the sample mean, s is the sample standard deviation, and the cubed term indicates that each deviation is raised to the third power.](data:image/png;base64,)

0 is symmetric

>0 is positively skewed

<0 negatively skewed

![The image displays three different normal distribution curves illustrating the concept of kurtosis. Each curve is labelled with its type of kurtosis. The curve labelled L represents a leptokurtic distribution, where kurtosis is greater than 3, indicating a sharper peak and fatter tails. The curve labelled M represents a mesokurtic distribution, where kurtosis equals 3, indicative of a standard normal distribution with moderate tail thickness. The curve labelled P represents a platykurtic distribution, where kurtosis is less than 3, showing a flatter peak and thinner tails compared to the standard normal distribution.](data:image/png;base64,)

![The formula for calculating the excess kurtosis of a dataset. K equals (n times (n plus 1) over ((n minus 1) times (n minus 2) times (n minus 3))) times the sum from i equals 1 to n of ((x sub i minus x bar) to the fourth power over s to the fourth) minus (3 times (n minus 1) squared over ((n minus 2) times (n minus 3))). Here, K represents the excess kurtosis, n is the number of observations, x sub i are the individual data points, x bar is the sample mean, and s is the sample standard deviation. The formula adjusts for sample size to provide a more accurate measure of tail thickness relative to the normal distribution.](data:image/png;base64,)

Central limit theorem(CTL) if you take a large random independent sample of a population then the sample mean will be approximately normally distributed, even if the initial population is not normal.

Null hypothesis is that there is no pattern or evidence

Alternative hypothesis H1 or Ha is the if there is a positive presence of that pattern or trend

One tailed tests detects something in one specific direction.

Two tailed tests detects an effect in either directions.

Statistical significance, often use 5%

P-value is chance of it happening if there was no pattern. Usually want it to be less than 5%

Pearson's correlation coefficient for linear relationships

![This is the formula for calculating the Pearson correlation coefficient, denoted as r. It shows r equals the sum of (x sub i minus x-bar) times (y sub i minus y-bar) divided by the square root of the sum of (x sub i minus x-bar squared) times the sum of (y sub i minus y-bar squared). Here, x sub i and y sub i represent the individual values of the variables x and y, x-bar and y-bar are the mean values of x and y, respectively. This formula calculates the degree of linear relationship between the two variables by normalising the product of their deviations from their respective means.](data:image/png;base64,)

t-statistics for Pearson correlation coefficient.

![This is the formula for calculating the t-statistic for a Pearson correlation coefficient. It shows t equals r times the square root of (n minus 2) divided by the square root of (1 minus r squared). Here, r represents the Pearson correlation coefficient, n is the number of data points, and the formula is used to determine the significance of the correlation by comparing it to a t-distribution.](data:image/png;base64,)

Degrees of freedom df =n -2

![The formula for a simple linear regression equation. It shows y equals a plus b times x. Here, y represents the dependent variable, a is the y-intercept of the regression line, b is the slope of the regression line, and x is the independent variable. This formula describes the relationship between x and y, where changes in x result in proportional changes in y.](data:image/png;base64,)

![The formula for calculating the slope (b) of the regression line in a simple linear regression. It shows b equals r times s sub y divided by s sub x. Here, b is the slope of the regression line, r is the Pearson correlation coefficient between the variables, s sub y is the standard deviation of the dependent variable (y), and s sub x is the standard deviation of the independent variable (x). This formula indicates how much y changes for a one-unit change in x, considering the strength and direction of their relationship.](data:image/png;base64,)

![The formula for calculating the y-intercept (a) of the regression line in a simple linear regression. It shows a equals y-bar minus b times x-bar. Here, a is the y-intercept of the regression line, y-bar represents the mean of the dependent variable (y), b is the slope of the regression line, and x-bar represents the mean of the independent variable (x). This formula calculates the point at which the regression line crosses the y-axis.](data:image/png;base64,)

 y = dependant variable, a = y intercept function, b = slope of the regression line, x = independent variable, r = Pearson’s correlation coefficient, S_y= standard deviation of y, S_x = standard deviation of x, y ̅ = mean of y sample and x ̅ = mean of x

The significance level is the threshold for determining whether a result is statistically significant. Commonly used significance levels are 0.05 (5%) and 0.01 (1%). A significance level of 0.05 means there is a 5% chance of rejecting the null hypothesis when it is actually true (Type I error).

From <[https://app.qa.com/course/statistical-investigations-ai-1698/understanding-statistical-significance-testing/?context_id=14511&context_resource=lp](https://app.qa.com/course/statistical-investigations-ai-1698/understanding-statistical-significance-testing/?context_id=14511&context_resource=lp)>

- P-value: The p-value is the probability of obtaining results at least as extreme as the observed results, assuming the null hypothesis is true. If the p-value is less than or equal to the significance level, the null hypothesis is rejected.

From <[https://app.qa.com/course/statistical-investigations-ai-1698/understanding-statistical-significance-testing/?context_id=14511&context_resource=lp](https://app.qa.com/course/statistical-investigations-ai-1698/understanding-statistical-significance-testing/?context_id=14511&context_resource=lp)>

- Test statistic: A test statistic is a standardised value calculated from sample data during a hypothesis test. Examples include t-statistics in t-tests and chi-square statistics in chi-square tests.

From <[https://app.qa.com/course/statistical-investigations-ai-1698/understanding-statistical-significance-testing/?context_id=14511&context_resource=lp](https://app.qa.com/course/statistical-investigations-ai-1698/understanding-statistical-significance-testing/?context_id=14511&context_resource=lp)>

- T-Test: Used to compare the means of two groups. There are different types of T-Tests, including:

- Independent samples T-Test: Compares the means of two independent groups.
- Paired samples T-Test: Compares the means of the same group at different times.
- One-sample T-Test: Compares the mean of a single group to a known value.

- ANOVA (Analysis of Variance): Used to compare the means of three or more groups. Variants of ANOVA include:

- One-Way ANOVA: Tests for differences in means across multiple groups.
- Two-Way ANOVA: Tests for the influence of two different categorical independent variables on a continuous dependent variable.

- Chi-Square Test: Used to examine the association between two categorical variables. There are different types of chi-square tests, such as:

- Chi-Square Test of Independence: Determines whether there is an association between two categorical variables.
- Chi-Square Goodness of Fit Test: Determines whether a sample matches an expected distribution.

- Correlation and Regression: Used to assess the relationship between two or more variables.

- Pearson’s Correlation Coefficient: Measures the linear relationship between two continuous variables.
- Simple Linear Regression: Examines the linear relationship between two continuous variables, allowing prediction of one variable based on the other.

- Non-Parametric Tests: Used when data do not meet the assumptions required for parametric tests.

- Mann-Whitney U Test: Compares differences between two independent groups.
- Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test: Compares differences between two related groups.
- Kruskal-Wallis Test: Compares differences between three or more groups.
